         <abstract>
            <p>Any financial decision criterion, which helps prevent incorrect management decisions and lessens agency problems in implementation by placing a premium on the development of sample information, is of value to the firm. Thus, we argue that agency considerations may account for firms' continued use of myopic criteria, which weigh heavily the timing and pattern of a project's cash flows when making capital expenditure decisions. We also argue that future financing/capital market decisions may prompt reliance upon these criteria. Finally, we show that dividends not only may play a role in reducing agency costs, but also are directly related to capital expenditure and financing/capital market decisions.</p>
         </abstract>
